Preheat your oven to 200°C. Halve the @butternut squash{1} lengthways (no need to peel!) and
scoop out the seeds. Chop into 1cm cubes. Halve the @red onion{1} (leaving the root on), then
peel and chop into wedges (four per half).

Put the squash on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle over some @olive oil{2%tbsp}. Season
with a pinch of @salt{} and a grind of @black pepper{} and toss to coat. Pop on the top
shelf of your oven. Roast until soft, ~{30-35%minutes}. After ~{20%minutes}, add the onion
to the baking tray, carefully toss together and roast until browned, ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a #frying pan{} on medium high heat. While the pan gets hot, pop the
@duck breasts{2} on a #chopping board{} skin-side up. Use a sharp #knife{} to make criss
crosses on the skin (don't cut through to the flesh), four lines going one way and four
going the other way diagonally. Season both sides of each duck breast with a pinch of
@salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Lay the duck skin-side down in your pan. Cook until the skin is crisp, ~{6-7%minutes},
turn and brown the flesh side for ~{1%minute}. Place on another baking tray (skin-side
up). Pop the baking tray on the middle shelf of your oven and roast for ~{8-10%minutes}.

> Cook for a couple mins more if you want it less rare.

When done, remove from your oven and drizzle on the @honey{1%tbsp}. Wrap loosely in
#foil{} to keep warm.

Break the @feta cheese{100%g} into small chunks roughly 1cm in size. Make the dressing
for the rocket in a #mixing bowl{} by adding the @cider vinegar{1%tbsp} to the
@olive oil{1%tbsp}. Whisk together using a #fork{}. Season with salt and pepper and add
half of the @sumac{1%tsp}, mix again.

When the butternut and onion are cooked, remove from the oven and sprinkle over the
remaining sumac.

Cut each duck breast into six thin slices. Add the @wild rocket{40%g} to your sumac
dressing and toss together. Lay the rocket out on your #plates{}. Nestle the butternut
and onion wedges amongst the rocket and then add the feta. Place the sliced duck on top
and drizzle over any juices left in the foil. Sprinkle the @dukkah mix{1} over the duck.
Enjoy!